# [SRV6OPS](../wg/srv6ops.html)

## Summary

The SRV6OPS working group session at IETF 126 was chaired by Dan Voyer, Dhruv Dhody, and Wei Chang. The session featured ten presentations covering operator deployment experiences (Deutsche Telekom, China Telecom, China Southern Power Grid, and SINET), open-source implementations (SONiC), and updates on active working group and individual drafts. 

Key advancements included progress towards Working Group Last Call (WGLC) for the deployment options draft, updates on the problem summary draft, and plans to initiate a working group adoption call for the addressing recommendations draft.

---

## Key Discussion Points

### 1. Operator Experiences and Implementations

#### [2.1 DT Road towards SRv6](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-21-dt-road-towards-srv6-00)
* **Presenter:** Nick (Deutsche Telekom)
* **Technical Details:** Deutsche Telekom (DT) presented its group-wide "Horizontal Digital Architecture" strategy, aiming to harmonize IP network layers across all local subsidiaries (ranging from hundreds to 50,000 nodes) using SRv6. DT selected the micro-SID (uSID) approach to simplify forwarding. For addressing, DT established a unified scheme utilizing the `5f::/16` block to prevent overlapping addresses and eliminate the need for renumbering. DT is also trialing end-to-end SRv6 connectivity into data centers (bypassing traditional technology translation layers) and virtual routers in cloud environments.
* **Discussion:**
  * Tom Hill (British Telecom) asked about the security model for cloud-interconnected virtual routers. Nick clarified that security designs are still in the proof-of-concept phase; they currently use direct connections but may deploy border protection routers and IPsec depending on partner capabilities.
  * Toby asked why DT preferred private space (`5f::/16`) over global IPv6 space. Nick confirmed that after extensive internal debate, the `5f::/16` block was chosen alongside a custom hierarchical formatting model underneath it.

#### [2.2 Practices for Migrating MPLS Networks to SRv6](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-22-practices-for-migrating-mpls-networks-to-srv6-00)
* **Presenter:** Yongxing Zhu (China Telecom)
* **Technical Details:** China Telecom shared its experience migrating multi-protocol MPLS networks (running OSPF, LDP, RSVP-TE, etc.) to SRv6. They defined two distinct migration paths:
  * *Greenfield Mode* (for scenarios where <50% of devices support SRv6): Deploying a parallel SRv6 network and progressively migrating capable access devices and services.
  * *Brownfield Mode* (for scenarios where $\ge$50% of devices are SRv6-capable): Enabling SRv6 on capable hardware, prioritizing SRv6 paths, and employing interworking gateways (via route re-origination and translation) for legacy segments.
  The design also leverages MP-BGP, hierarchical GUA IP allocation, and in-band performance measurement via alternate marking (RFC 9341, RFC 9342, and RFC 9447) and telemetry.
* **Discussion:**
  * Himanshu Shah (Ciena) raised a scenario involving dual-stack/dual-capability (SR-MPLS and SRv6) egress PEs running L3VPN and asked how route distribution and BGP peering with the Route Reflector (RR) were managed. Yongxing Zhu took the detailed explanation offline.
  * Dan (BHP) asked why China Telecom did not use SRv6 compression (micro-SID) and why they switched address families from L3VPN to EVPN. Yongxing Zhu responded that in 95% of their network paths, the end-to-end hop count is under 10, meaning compression was not initially critical. Further discussion was deferred offline.

#### [2.3 SRv6 @ SONiC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-23-srv6-sonic-01)
* **Presenter:** Ahnaf Salam (Cisco)
* **Technical Details:** Ahnaf Salam outlined the 5-year journey of implementing SRv6 in the SONiC open-source network operating system. Features include static fabric routing for AI back-ends, L3VPN, IPv4/IPv6 GRT, and an SRv6 SID manager. The static SRv6 micro-SID fabric was merged into the May 2025 SONiC release (~120 PRs) and deployed in Microsoft's Fairwater AI data center. Future work (2026) centers on AI scale-out WAN architectures requiring traffic engineering (TE) and fast reroute (FRR) in BGP-only fabrics.
* **Discussion:**
  * Alex asked for clarification on the open-source status of the Switch Abstraction Interface (SAI) layer for proprietary silicon. Ahnaf Salam explained that while the SAI API definition is open-source (OCP-governed), the underlying ASIC SDK implementations remain proprietary to individual silicon vendors.
  * Toby inquired about support for End.DT vs End.DX endpoints in SONiC and the Linux kernel. Ahnaf Salam noted that while SONiC and the SAI layer support both behaviors, gaps primarily existed within the FRR routing stack implementation for End.DX.
  * An unidentified participant asked about the release and upstreaming timeline. Ahnaf Salam indicated that SONiC operates on a bi-annual release cadence, and any routing feature must first be stabilized upstream in FRR.
  * Keyur Patel suggested that the presentation should focus more on operational metrics (scale, hardware interoperability challenges) and less on product positioning. 
  * Dhruv Dhody requested that the authors compile operational feedback from the Alibaba and Microsoft deployments to enrich the working group's Best Current Practice (BCP) documents.

