### 3. Individual Drafts and Proposals

#### [3.3 Addressing Recommendations](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-33-addressing-recommendations-00)
* **Presenter:** Jakub Horn
* **Technical Details:** Version -02 of this draft incorporates a new section covering "replace-C-SID" compression alongside the existing micro-SID (uSID) text to ensure completeness, as both compression methods are defined in the same base RFC.
* **Discussion:** The presenter requested a working group adoption call. Co-chair Dan Voyer asked if there were any objections; finding none, he agreed to launch the adoption call on the mailing list.

#### [3.4 SRv6 in AI Backend](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-34-srv6-in-ai-backend-01)
* **Presenter:** Ahnaf Salam (Cisco)
* **Technical Details:** This draft covers the design of static SRv6 uSID fabrics for AI back-ends, highlighting deterministic path selection, low MTU overhead, and congestion feedback. It also details the integration of Multi-bus Reliable Control (MRC) with SRv6 to handle packet trimming and ECN without relying on dynamic routing protocols (IGP/BGP). Microsoft and Oracle operators have joined as co-authors.
* **Discussion:** Justin (NVIDIA) cautioned that while the physical fabric configuration becomes simpler with a static design, the underlying control and monitoring planes remain highly complex, and this operational complexity should be explicitly documented in the draft.

#### [3.5 SRv6 in End-to-End DC Frontend](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-35-srv6-in-end-to-end-dc-frontend-01)
* **Presenter:** Ahnaf Salam (Cisco)
* **Technical Details:** This draft addresses the optimization of WAN-to-DC front-end boundaries, removing protocol translation and tunnel mesh overhead through end-to-end SRv6. Version -01 integrates actual deployment use cases from Nebius and Deutsche Telekom.
* **Discussion:** The authors requested working group adoption.

#### [3.6 SFC Deployments](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-36-sfc-deployments-00)
* **Presenter:** Wataru Shinohara
* **Technical Details:** Wataru Shinohara shared lessons from deploying SRv6 Service Function Chaining (SFC) for a remote video production service over SINET (an academic IPv6 backbone in Japan spanning three data centers). Key findings included:
  1. *Service SID Uniqueness:* Risks of SID collision require coordination between the SDN controller and local service function managers.
  2. *Component Placement:* Centralizing the VNF manager and controller in a single DC reduces exposure to inter-DC link failures.
  3. *Failure Recovery:* Fast Reroute (FRR) restores connectivity but does not preserve application state, necessitating application-level buffering or state synchronization.
  4. *Observability:* Operators must monitor both the network layer and the application payload to ensure correct transcoding and processing.
* **Discussion:**
  * An unidentified speaker asked if this draft relies on the active Spring SFC draft. Wataru Shinohara confirmed that it aligns with the Spring SRv6 SFC architecture.
  * Thomas Graf noted the challenge of multi-layer encapsulation visibility and suggested reviewing the ongoing IPFIX multilayer encapsulation work in the OPSAWG.
  * Dan (BHP) asked about the packet flow behavior and resilience if the middle transit data center (Kanagawa) experienced a total failure. Wataru Shinohara explained that video sources are split and distributed across sites (such as Okinawa and Ishikawa), and agreed to provide a detailed routing breakdown offline.

#### [3.7 ESP Protection for Services](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-srv6ops-37-esp-protection-for-services-00)
* **Presenter:** Unidentified Presenter (China Southern Power Grid)
* **Technical Details:** China Southern Power Grid presented a use case where secure dispatch networks and unencrypted integrated data networks are being combined onto a unified SRv6 infrastructure. They proposed using a single BGP control plane to negotiate IPsec/ESP parameters for protected traffic flows. The data plane carries an outer SRv6 header with an ESP-encrypted payload inside. BGP advertisements specify which prefixes must be protected using a newly assigned IANA BGP tunnel type for ESP-protected payloads.
* **Discussion:** The presenter requested working group feedback and adoption. Due to time constraints, further discussion was directed to the mailing list.

